commit.message:
Refactor into separate library and executable.

This is a lot of work to solve a stupid problem: when deploying the
executable, there's no good way to drop the ".py" extension on-the-fly
to wind up with a command named "check_multiple" as the README suggests.
Of course, I can rename the script from "check_multiple.py" to simply
"check_multiple", but that breaks the test suite, which insists on
being able to import the module containing the tests (which it can't
do if the "module" is missing its .py extension).

To ensure that the command can be called with "check_multiple", and to
keep the test suite working, this commit splits the executable and
library into two files. The executable now lives at bin/check_multiple,
and is extensionless. The library, on the other hand, lives in its own
package, lib/check_multiple. The check_multiple.py module within that
package can be imported by python, and can therefore be tested.

Having the two files separate is a bit annoying, because now you can't
just run the thing during development, but there's an easy PYTHONPATH
hack to make that work. I've added it to the README.
README.md: mention the output format.
MANIFEST.in: list the documentation files to be included in a release.
check_multiple.py: mark executable.
setup.py,README.md: mention that I've tested pythons 3.5 through 3.8.

README.md: update to reflect recent changes, and word-wrap.

The mode names have changed and the test suite output looks a bit
different now, so the README needs to be updated. I've also word-
wrapped everything, and added a "Requirements" list stating that
python-3.5 or greater is required.

check_multiple.py: switch from one/all modes to worst/best.

Now that we have the ability to handle WARNING results, the modes
"one" and "all" are misnomers. Instead what we're really returning is
the best or worst overall result. In the past, with only two
possibilities, we had best == one and worst == all. But now we want
probably want to return WARNING and not CRITICAL if every individual
check returns WARNING. The names "best" and "worst" make it easier
to tell the program what you want.

Support WARNING as well, and return the best/worst overall status.

Instead of forcing a result of either OK or CRITICAL, it may sometimes
be desireable to return WARNING. For example, in mode "one", if all
checks return WARNING, you probably want an overall result of WARNING
as well, because that's the "best" status you've seen.

This commit adds support for reporting and returning warnings, and
updates the test suite to check all 3^3 combinations (in both modes)
of individual statuses.

check_multiple.py: rename "failure" and "success" to match exit codes.

Instead of "failure", the name "critical" is more accurate. Likewise
"ok" is better than "success". This is in preparation for introducing
a "warning" count in addition to ok/critical.
Add a basic test suite that checks our exit codes.

check_multiple.py: use constants for the various exit codes.

The Nagios plugin API specifies the return codes that mean "OK",
"WARNING", "CRITICAL", and "UNKNOWN". This commit replaces the
magic numbers for those codes with constants like EXIT_OK.
setup.py: new file to ease installation and release building.

check_multiple.py: overhaul to support python-3.x.

Tested with python-3.6, but I've tried to make choices backwards-
compatible to python-3.5. Specifically, we use the subprocess.run()
method that only exists in python-3.5, but avoid the "capture_output"
and "text" keywords to that method that only exist in python-3.7.

A comprehensive list of changes would be too long to include here. A
large number of minor refactorings were done in the process of the
large refactorings necessary to adopt the python-3.x APIs.

check_multiple.py: don't specify the number of processes.

If you leave off the "number of processes" argument to ThreadPool(),
then Python will use the number of CPUs that the machine has available.
This seems like a more robust choice than hard-coding the value 5.

README.md: update example usage and output.

The command-line syntax has changed, so the README needs an update to
match.

check_multiple.py: minor tweaks to the --help output.

Python creates the description of the --help flag, and does so without
capitalization or punctuation. For consistency, this commit makes the
other two "command" and "mode" arguments display the same way. I have
also tried to reword the description of the "mode" argument in a
simpler way.

check_multiple.py: drop "s" from the "commands" argument name.

The list of commands should be thought of as (command, command, ...)
rather than as (commands, commands, ...) since each additional
argument is a single command. This commit changes the name of the
multi-argument "commands" to "command", so that the usage string
conforms to that interpretation.
update words
